Public Mutation Database and Ovarian Cancer Survival Analysis

I. Objectives

The best way to learn how to work with cancer genomic data analysis is to use the public big data freely accessible by anyone. Cancer’s main etiology is somatic mutations and therefore it is natural that NGS is applied to analyzing cancer genomics. Germline DNA does not get mutated easily throughout lifespan, but cancer DNAs undergo a variety of mutations, which is detected by NGS. Humanity’s approach to curing cancer is to make a big ass repository where all sorts of cancer genomics data are stored and use collective intelligence to tackle the problem. We will see how a data analysis over TCGA public multi-omics data resulted in a magnificent study published in JAMA. We will also learn how we can utilize genomic big data in our research by looking at the example of BRCA1 and BRCA2 variation and consequent survival analysis.

II. Introduction

TCGA provides integrative repository of genomic, transcriptomic, epigenomic, and clinical data over 33 types of cancer. In this chapter, the results from study “Association of BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations with survival in ovarian cancer”1 is reproduced. This study elucidated the role of BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutation and methylation associated with ovarian cancer, which had been quite a controversy up till that time. Also, this paper achieves the feat of publishing in one of the most prestigious journals only by using the publicly available TCGA data. It also signaled the paradigm shift from experiment-centered to data-centered science.

I dare say that cancer is a disease of genome itself, accompanying countless mutations. It is dire that we are able to discern the source of mutation in a data: whether it is from a germline mutation or a somatic mutation. The study we are referring to removed germline mutations discovered in the patients’ blood samples from ovarian tissue sample data of BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations, which leaves us with only somatic mutations to look at. (Q: But aren’t there germline mutations that contribute to the predisposition to cancer?) BRCA1 methylation data is obtained from methylation chip experimental results. For simplicity, regarding convenience and purpose of this practice, we only use data from 500 probes.

  • somatic mutation data: JAMA_Mutation.txt
  • DNA methylation data: JAMA_BRCA1_Methyl.txt
  • Microarray data: JAMA_Expression.txt (gene expression data of only 500 probes -> RNA)
  • Clinical variable data: JAMA_Clinical.csv

Each file looks like the following:

JAMA_Mutation

JAMA_BRCA1_Methyl

JAMA_Expression

JAMA_Clinical

IV. Classifying patient groups

Do BRCA1, BRCA2 mutations and methylation status affect ovarian cancer prognosis? Let’s proceed with a survival analysis to find out. First of all we classify the patient groups into 4 groups: BRCA1 mutation, BRCA2 mutation, BRCA1 methylation, and normal.

If we look at what mut looks like,

str(mut)

Put samples from mut that have gene name “BRCA1” and “BRCA2” into their respective variables brca1.mut, brca2.mut. Take the index of rows that have gene name (second column) “BRCA1”, “BRCA2”, and take only the sample name (first column) as a vector. If a sample name occurs multiple times, just take one by using unique.

brca1.mut <- unique(as.character(mut[which(mut[,2]=="BRCA1"), 1]))
brca2.mut <- unique(as.character(mut[which(mut[,2]=="BRCA2"), 1]))

Draw a heatmap that has high correlation with BRCA1 expression level. If the methylation probe has particularly high correlation (0.3<) with BRCA1 expression level or particularly low correlation w/ BRCA1 expression level (-0.3>), print it out in a heatmap. As we’ve seen from above, use the apply function to find the pearson correlation coefficient between BRCA1 expression level and each methylation probe’s beta value.

exp.cor <- apply(met[,-1], 1, function(x) cor(x, brca1.exp))
## Warning in cor(x, brca1.exp): 표준편차가 0입니다

# row-wise, bring 
TestMatrix <- met[which(abs(exp.cor)>0.3), -1]
# Next, find the samples where BRCA1 methylation patterns are different. (because we took abs of exp.cor)
heatmap(as.matrix(TestMatrix), scale="row", col=heat.colors(12)) # Draw heatmap

# If you want to reverse it, you can use rev
heatmap(as.matrix(TestMatrix), scale="row", col=rev(heat.colors(12)))

# Curiously enough, the default is set at reverse of heat.colors(12)

# or you can also use RColorBrewer

library(RColorBrewer)
coul <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(8, "PiYG"))(25)
heatmap(as.matrix(TestMatrix), scale="row", col = coul)

heat.colors() function takes number of heat gradients as the argument.

Refer to R Graph Gallery for more info about heatmap function and color palette: r-graph-gallery

Now, hclust performs what is called the hierarchical clustering. (Refer to https://bioinformaticsandme.tistory.com/145, https://www.displayr.com/what-is-hierarchical-clustering/, https://ratsgo.github.io/machine%20learning/2017/04/18/HC/) The endpoint of hierarchical clustering is a set of clusters where each cluster is distinct from each other cluster, and the objects within each cluster are broadly similar to each other.

AA <- hclust(dist(t(TestMatrix)))
plot(AA)

M <- identify(AA)

identify(AA) is the function where you select the cluster and take the sample names of that group from dendrogram graphic viewer to a list, by clicking the cluster on the right. So you gotta execute it in the console to proceed to the next. Then you gotta press ESC to stop selecting and assign the obtained list to M.

You can also use hclust to divide the clusters into certain groups and choose among them with an index.

plot(AA)
M <- rect.hclust(AA, h=1.3, border=0)[2]

VI. Survival Analysis

Lastly, we do survival analysis using clinical data.

Set types of samples (brca1.met, brca1.mut, brca2.mut) and gsub to unify format

dim(cli)
## [1] 317  44
type <- c(rep('wild', 317)) # Repeat 317 times of wild and make it into a vector

Assign patient barcode to names.

names(type) <- cli[, 1] # The first column is patient barcode.

Change the format because they’re different. brca1.met has dot (“.”) and brca1.mut has dash (“-”).

brca1.met <- gsub(".", "-", brca1.met, fixed=T) 
#fixed = TRUE argument means the pattern is a string to be matched as is, not as a regular expression.

Survival Analysis

library(survival)
out <- survfit(Surv(cli$days_to_last_followup) ~ type)

This means, make survival analysis object with clinical data’s days_to_last_followup column value with type as the variable to analyze against. There are total of four categories for survival analysis: wild, brca1.met, brca1.mut, brca2.mut.

color <- c("green", "blue", "red", "black") # make vector to designate each of the four categories
plot(out, col=color, main="Association of BRCA1/2 Mutations with Survival", xlab="Time, days", ylab="Proportion") #plot

legend(4200, 0.9, c("BRCA1 mutation", "BRCA1 methylation", "BRCA2 mutation", "wild"), col=color, lty=1, lwd=3)

Rest of the clusters (groups) don’t show much of difference from wildtype Kaplan-Meier survival curve.

However, BRCA2 mutation shows notable difference from wildtype in survival rate. Therefore, BRCA2 mutation shows better prognosis than wildtype and BRCA1 mutation, BRCA1 differential expression (differential methylation) group.

However, does differential methylation directly correlate with differential expression? I’m not sure.
